label.value: elongated J-shaped vegetative cell with curved interphase microtubules

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is elongated, is curved along the long axis to form a "J" shape, and contains cytoplasmic microtubules that curve to follow the long axis of the cell. In a curved cell, the long axis follows a smooth bend rather than a straight line. In a J-shaped cell, the curve is centered away from the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.

definition.value: Microtubules in these cells are longer than in wild-type cells, but they are not regarded as elongated because they are normal in proportion to cell length.

label.value: delayed onset of UV-damage excision repair

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which UV-damage excision repair begins later than normal. UV-damage excision repair is a DNA repair process that is initiated by an endonuclease that introduces a single-strand incision immediately 5' of a UV-induced damage site, and that acts on both cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers (CPDs) and pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts (6-4PPs).

label.value: decreased UV-damage excision repair during mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which UV-damage excision repair occurs to a lower extent than normal during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle. UV-damage excision repair is a DNA repair process that is initiated by an endonuclease that introduces a single-strand incision immediately 5' of a UV-induced damage site, and that acts on both cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers (CPDs) and pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts (6-4PPs).

label.value: aggregated actin cortical patches during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin cortical patches cluster together more than normal.

label.value: decreased mitotic recombination at hotspot

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of mitotic recombination at one or more recombination hotspots is decreased to the background level. The basal rate of recombination (i.e. away from hotspots) may remain normal or may be decreased.

label.value: globally decreased mitotic recombination

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of mitotic recombination is decreased both at recombination hotspots and elsewhere in the genome.

label.value: decreased meiotic recombination at hotspot

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of meiotic recombination at one or more recombination hotspots is decreased to the background level. The basal rate of recombination (i.e. away from hotspots) may remain normal or may be decreased.

label.value: globally decreased meiotic recombination

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of meiotic recombination is decreased both at recombination hotspots and elsewhere in the genome.

label.value: inviable after spore germination with elongated germ tube and fragmented nucleus

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell that has an elongated germ tube and a nucleus that is broken into multiple small fragments, and does not go on to give rise to a viable cell population.

label.value: abolished double-strand break repair

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which double-strand break repair does not occur.

label.value: normal number of Rad52 foci during cellular response to bleomycin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to bleomycin.

label.value: abnormal DNA/DNA annealing activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of DNA/DNA annealing activity is abnormal.

label.value: decreased DNA/DNA annealing activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of DNA/DNA annealing activity is decreased.

label.value: swollen elongated cell with enlarged nucleus

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is swollen, is elongated, and in which the nucleus is larger than normal. The cell contains one nucleus and no septum. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

definition.value: The distinction between this phenotype and centrally constricted (dumbbell-shaped) cells (FYPO:0000779) is that swollen elongated cells do not have a constriction along the long axis. Swollen elongated cells may have a uniform diameter, or may be swollen only around the nucleus. This phenotype is usually seen in diploid cells, so consider also annotating to 'increased spontaneous diploidization' (FYPO:0000252).

label.value: abolished protein localization to microtubule during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to one or more microtubules does not occur during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal telomeric DNA separation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic sister chromatid separation is abnormal at the telomeric regions. The remainder of the sister chromatids may or may not separate normally.

label.value: decreased proteolysis during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of hydrolysis of peptide bonds within a protein is decreased. All proteolysis may be affected, or only cleavage of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: slow vegetative cell population growth followed by return to normal growth rate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is initially slower than normal, and remains slow for several generations, after which the population resumes growing at a normal or near-normal rate.

definition.value: This population growth pattern is often seen with mutations that affect telomere maintenance.

label.value: normal telomere 3' overhang length during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the length of the single-stranded telomeric 3' overhang is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abolished molecular function

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific molecular function is absent.

label.value: abnormal biological process

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific biological process is abnormal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: abolished biological process

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific biological process does not occur.

label.value: abolished cellular process

value.value: A phenotype in which a specific cellular process does not occur.

label.value: normal growth on okadaic acid

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing okadaic acid.

label.value: decreased break-induced loss of heterozygosity

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which one of two different alleles of a gene is lost less frequently than normal after a double-strand break forms nearby.

definition.value: This phenotype may be observed in diploid cells, or in cells that have two copies of one or more reporter loci but are otherwise haploid.

label.value: increased break-induced loss of heterozygosity

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which one of two different alleles of a gene is lost more frequently than normal after a double-strand break forms nearby.

definition.value: This phenotype may be observed in diploid cells, or in cells that have two copies of one or more reporter loci but are otherwise haploid.

label.value: abolished break-induced loss of heterozygosity via chromosomal translocation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosomal translocation that would result in the loss of one of two different alleles of a gene does not occur.

definition.value: This phenotype may be observed in diploid cells, or in cells that have two copies of one or more reporter loci but are otherwise haploid. Loss of heterozygosity associated with chromosomal translocation may result from allelic crossover or break-induced replication. In cells with this phenotype, loss of heterozygosity may or may not occur via a different mechanism, such as chromosomal truncation.

label.value: abnormal telomere assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which telomere assembly, i.e. the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a telomere at a double-stranded DNA end, is abnormal.

label.value: telomere assembly at double-strand break site

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which telomere assembly occurs at one or more chromosome ends generated by a double-strand break.

definition.value: This phenotype can lead to loss of heterozygosity at loci near the break.

label.value: decreased number of cells with 1C DNA content

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a lower than normal number of cells contain 1C DNA content.

label.value: decreased cellular glycerol level during cellular response to osmotic stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of glycerol measured in a cell during a cellular response to osmotic stress is lower than normal.

label.value: decreased cellular glycerol level during cellular response to non-ionic osmotic stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of glycerol measured in a cell during a cellular response to non-ionic osmotic stress is lower than normal.

label.value: abolished double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ) does not occur.

label.value: abolished protein localization to chromatin at MCB promoters

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at promoters that contain MCB sites is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal microtubule-based movement during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which microtubule-based movement is abnormal.

label.value: decreased microtubule-based movement during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which microtubule-based movement occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased spatial extent of interphase microtubule polymerization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cytoplasmic microtubule polymerization, i.e. the addition of tubulin dimers to the plus end of a cytoplasmic microtubule during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle, does not continue until microtubules reach the ends of the cell.

label.value: abnormal maintenance of protein location at cell tip during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a protein is localized to one or both cell tip(s), but then remains there for a longer or shorter time than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal cell polarity

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the establishment or maintenance of cell polarity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: Use this term if all aspects of cell polarity are normal, including selection of polarity landmark sites, and polar growth at landmarks.

label.value: protein mislocalized to non-growing cell tip

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a protein that is not normally found at the non-growing cell tip is observed there.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used to annotate any case where a protein is found at the non-growing cell tip in a mutant, but not in wild type. In some cases, there may be enough additional information to annotate to 'abnormal protein localization' (FYPO:0000443) or one of its descendants. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein localization to actomyosin contractile ring during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the actomyosin contractile ring is decreased during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to cell tip during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cell tip is increased during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, lysed cell

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce an inviable cell that does not divide, and eventually lyses.

label.value: abnormal glutamate synthase (NADH) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of glutamate synthase activity using NADH as a cofactor is abnormal.

label.value: abolished glutamate synthase (NADH) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which glutamate synthase activity using NADH as a cofactor is absent.

label.value: abolished glutamate dehydrogenase (NADP+) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which glutamate dehydrogenase activity using NAPD+ as a cofactor is absent.

label.value: normal glutamate synthase (NADH) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of glutamate synthase activity using NADH as a cofactor is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal glutamate dehydrogenase (NADP+) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of glutamate dehydrogenase activity using NAPD+ as a cofactor is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: swollen vegetative cell with normal cell length

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is normal length but has a larger volume than normal.

label.value: decreased filamentous actin level

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of filamentous actin measured the cell is lower than normal when the cell is in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. The total actin level (globular and filamentous actin) may be normal or abnormal.
